31:11.200 --> 31:16.200
National Standards

31:16.200 --> 31:22.200
As we have seen, national standards are very diverse

31:22.200 --> 31:29.200
and sometimes provide incomparable information.

31:29.200 --> 31:33.200
Such a variety of national standards

31:33.200 --> 31:38.200
has caused a need for the preparation

31:38.200 --> 31:43.200
of international standards on financial accounting

31:43.200 --> 31:46.200
in the same standards.

31:46.200 --> 31:50.200
Here, the object of standardization

31:50.200 --> 31:54.200
is not accounting in general,

31:54.200 --> 32:00.200
but preparation and presentation of financial accounting.

32:00.200 --> 32:05.200
We are talking about external accounting,

32:05.200 --> 32:09.200
general accounting,

32:09.200 --> 32:14.200
accounting used by shareholders,

32:14.200 --> 32:19.200
creditors, clients, workers, and the public.

32:19.200 --> 32:22.200
Special financial accounting,

32:22.200 --> 32:25.200
such as commission and tax accounting,

32:25.200 --> 32:31.200
are not considered international standards.

32:31.200 --> 32:36.200
Today, there is a global accounting system

32:36.200 --> 32:40.200
based on international standards.

32:40.200 --> 32:45.200
Since 1983, the International Standards Committee

32:45.200 --> 32:49.200
of the Financial Accounting has been working in London.

32:49.200 --> 32:52.200
It is an independent body

32:52.200 --> 32:58.200
whose goal is to unify accounting principles

32:58.200 --> 33:02.200
used by companies around the world

33:02.200 --> 33:06.200
for financial accounting.

33:06.200 --> 33:09.200
By the end of the 20th century,

33:09.200 --> 33:14.200
more than 100 countries were represented

33:14.200 --> 33:19.200
in the International Standards Committee.

33:19.200 --> 33:24.200
Today, international standards are used

33:24.200 --> 33:28.200
as a basis for national requirements

33:28.200 --> 33:31.200
for financial accounting in many countries,

33:31.200 --> 33:36.200
as an international standard for those countries

33:36.200 --> 33:41.200
that develop their own requirements for accounting,

33:41.200 --> 33:45.200
including the main developed countries,

33:45.200 --> 33:48.200
the remaining number of new markets,

33:48.200 --> 33:53.200
such as China, Asian countries, Central Europe,

33:53.200 --> 33:56.200
Russia, and the CIS countries.

33:56.200 --> 34:01.200
Third, transnational corporations are used

34:01.200 --> 34:05.200
to make their own accounting.

34:05.200 --> 34:08.200
Fourth, fund exchanges

34:08.200 --> 34:12.200
requiring foreign and national companies

34:12.200 --> 34:17.200
to provide financial reports in compliance with the International Standards Committee

34:17.200 --> 34:22.200
are also used by regional organizations,

34:22.200 --> 34:25.200
such as the European Commission,

34:25.200 --> 34:30.200
which in 1995 announced

34:30.200 --> 34:35.200
that it relies on the International Standards Committee

34:35.200 --> 34:41.200
to prepare documents reflecting the needs of the capital market.

34:41.200 --> 34:46.200
International standards are also used

34:46.200 --> 34:49.200
by all economic entities,

34:49.200 --> 34:53.200
such as large corporations, holdings,

34:53.200 --> 34:57.200
that have foreign capital.

34:57.200 --> 35:02.200
The International Standards Committee is the most important element

35:02.200 --> 35:06.200
of modern corporate governance.

35:06.200 --> 35:12.200
It is the basis for timely, objective information

35:12.200 --> 35:17.200
for all interested users.

35:17.200 --> 35:23.200
