01:07:36.200 --> 01:07:51.200
The principles of the financial account also give the concept of the main elements of financial accountability. What are assets, obligations, and the concept of capital?

01:07:51.200 --> 01:08:06.200
Assets are the resources of a controlled company that arose as a result of past periods and from which economic benefits are expected in the future.

01:08:06.200 --> 01:08:18.200
What can it be? It is the main resources, non-material assets, reserves, ready-made products, goods, money.

01:08:18.200 --> 01:08:32.200
Control is the unlimited access and at the same time the ability to prohibit access to other people's rights to future economic benefits.

01:08:32.200 --> 01:08:54.200
Property is not a necessary obligation. It is a current debt formed as a result of past periods and from which the outflow of resources containing economic benefits is expected in the future.

01:08:54.200 --> 01:09:09.200
What are the obligations? We have taken a loan. We have employees. We have to pay them a salary at the end of the month. At the end of the month, it is an obligation.

01:09:09.200 --> 01:09:35.200
Employees earn their right to vacation during the working period. Therefore, we have to create a reserve for the payment of vacation payments. We have received a commodity, but we have not paid for it.

01:09:36.200 --> 01:10:01.200
Capital is given as a balancing factor in international standards. It is the difference between assets and obligations. It is the remaining share in the company's assets after all obligations are paid.

01:10:01.200 --> 01:10:21.200
Sometimes it is called pure assets. It is not only the established capital. It can be both established capital, that is, the capital with the owner, and the capital that the company has already earned.

01:10:21.200 --> 01:10:44.200
It is part of the unallocated profit that comes here, what is left of the company. It is reserve capital. It is additional capital that comes here. International financial reporting standards use different assessment bases.

01:10:45.200 --> 01:11:09.200
These are the initial costs, the current costs, the realized costs, the allocated costs, the potential obligations, and the fair costs.

01:11:10.200 --> 01:11:24.200
As we have already said, the financial reporting system is a living organism, the general direction of which is from historical value to fair value.

01:11:24.200 --> 01:11:46.200
Fair value is the value at which assets can be exchanged, and obligations can be paid off as a result of a deal between the informed, independent, and those who wish to make this deal.

01:11:46.200 --> 01:12:13.200
This assessment is widely presented in the standards themselves. In the financial reporting system, income and expenses are included. Income is the return on the profit in the reporting period in the form of asset inflow or obligation reduction, which leads to capital increase, not related to the share of shareholders.

01:12:14.200 --> 01:12:26.200
When income appears, we provide a service, we sell a product, a finished product, we get income, we have to pay it.

01:12:27.200 --> 01:12:45.200
Expenses are the reduction of economic benefits in the form of asset inflow or obligation reduction, which leads to capital decrease, not related to the share of shareholders.

01:12:45.200 --> 01:13:09.200
In the production process, we use raw materials, we use labor, we have to pay it, we use machines, equipment, that is, basic means.

01:13:09.200 --> 01:13:17.200
All this leads to a reduction of economic benefits. These are the expenses of the enterprise.

